Package frc.robot

Class ClientServerPipeline

java.lang.Object
frc.robot.ClientServerPipeline
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Runnable
public class ClientServerPipeline
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Runnable
Acts as a bridge between the internet-connected bot and the terrible robot. Implements Runnable because the run() method will create a new thread and prevent exiting.

    • run

      public void run()
      Creates a new Thread and runs this code on it. Due to sync stuff, it is just like starting anew. We here at jojo2357 inc do NOT mess with java async for it is too messy. Only use this when running a dedicated pipeline
      Specified by:
      run in interface java.lang.Runnable

    • updatePipeline

      public void updatePipeline()
      Runs differently on client and server.

      Client: listens for command messages and handles them with MessageHandler.onMessageReceived(AbstractCommand.AbstractCommandData)

      Server: Checks for bot replies, checks for new warnings, updates alarm statuses, and listens for resets

    • wipeSounds

      public boolean wipeSounds()
      Runs different on server and on client.

      On server: unsets all alarms and all but the current message playing.

      On client: notifies the server and unsets all alarm flags

      Returns:
      Server: true if sounds wiped.

      Client: NetworkTableEntry.setBoolean(boolean)
